##What is the truth of Germany's epidemic prevention?

New Coronaviruses are speeding up the ravages of old Europe.

As far as the number of confirmed cases is concerned, Italy once surpassed South Korea as the largest overseas epidemic country, with a high mortality rate, while France and Germany ranked fifth and sixth Slovakia, Malta, Faroe Islands, Moldova, and other small countries in eastern Europe, Liechtenstein, the Vatican and so on have all been hit.

But there is one number to watch in the surge: The number of confirmed deaths in Germany of more than 1,000 is still zero. But that may not be reason for premature optimism in the EU's largest economy and population.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
###What's the secret?

"If we were looking at a 3 percent mortality rate, there would be six or seven deaths by now, " he said, "But we don't really have that many, " German virologist professor Christian Drosten said in an interview with North German radio station NDR on March 5. "Our death toll is zero. "

Professor Dorsten, who helped the CDC map the SARS genome in April 2003, is regarded as Germany's foremost expert in the field. Because Spann, the health minister, has only a formal bachelor's degree and a master's degree from an online school, his ability to lead the health ministry has been questioned, leading the Chinese community to refer to him as the German version of Zhong Nanshan.

Four days after Dorsten's interview, the number of confirmed cases in Germany has nearly tripled, but the death toll remains zero.

Indeed, compared with 366 deaths in Italy and 19 in France, Germany has a rare zero mortality rate, with 17 and 22 deaths in Spain and the United States, which have far fewer confirmed cases than Germany.

"Our advantage over other countries is that we are still in the relatively early stages of an outbreak, " Dorsten said, compared with Italy, where the new coronavirus had already spread in January, imported cases in Germany are tracked immediately.

As early as February 26, the most serious outbreak in north rhine-westphalia and the first cases of contact with the crowd has been screened, including the state of Bafu, "patient 1" is the first time after returning from a trip to Milan to the hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: The Times

Besides taking advantage of the time lag, there are deeper reasons why Germany can do a better job of reducing mortality than other European countries, such as Spain and the Netherlands, where imported cases originate.

"there is a systemic difference between Germany and other countries, " Dorsten says, citing advanced laboratory conditions and the spread of large-scale testing driven by market forces as the secret of Germany's zero-mortality rate.

Germany has the largest number of biosafety rated P4 laboratories in Europe. Four laboratories are more than the UK and France combined, and if you count the three P4 laboratories in Switzerland, the pan-german-speaking region is home to more than half of Europe's (including Russia) top-tier biological laboratories.

All German institutions spend an average of $38bn a year in Europe, far ahead of France's $23bn and the UK's $14bn, according to Statista.

Second, unlike in Japan or parts of the United States, where only visible symptoms are allowed to be detected, any German who suspects he or she is infected with a new crown can call the health department's hotline, and proceed to a designated location for testing. Detection points are located on the side of the City Hall in the city centre to ensure that suspected cases can walk to avoid the use of public transport to expand the spread of infection.

These measures ensure that patients with mild illness can be properly handled in the first place, to avoid their development into severe cases. At present, more than 80% of the confirmed cases in Germany are mild and asymptomatic, while only 9 cases are critical.

As early as January this year, Germany with market-oriented means to establish a large-scale testing of the foundation. For example, one of Germany's largest health insurance companies, Techniker Krankenkasse (TK) , reimburses $59 if a person has traveled to an affected area or had contact with a confirmed patient. According to Tib Molbiol, a berlin-based testing reagent producer, a 100-pack of the kit costs 250 euros, which is less than 10 euros per test, even after shipping and labour costs.

Because health care providers earn a portion of their income from the price differential for new coronavirus testing, testing sites are often open to even asymptomatic patients.

On the other hand, Germany's current three-level system for the treatment of new crown disease has also ensured the full release of medical resources to the greatest extent possible, avoiding the critical condition of patients who can not be treated in time.

In the capital city of Berlin, for example, a 24-hour hotline will be used by professionals to screen patients based on their symptoms and travel history: those with more severe symptoms and those in need of clinical treatment will be admitted to a hospital immediately; Mild cases or suspected cases will be referred to the neighborhood General Clinic (Artzpraxis) , while asymptomatic patients will be referred to the health department for testing at major testing sites. A decentralized, collaborative approach to epidemic prevention can isolate, treat, and reduce mortality in the first place.

A two-tier system of clinics or family doctors plus general hospitals is also at the heart of Germany's current health-care system. In general, patients are admitted to the General Hospital only upon presentation of a referral form from a clinic or a family doctor, and it often takes more than half a day to get to the general hospital without advice.

In addition, all surgical arrangements in Germany are graded according to the level of urgency, and hospitals have the right to postpone, if necessary, lower-level surgeries that are not detrimental to health, thanks to the slightly cumbersome appointment system, to make sure the new patients get priority treatment.

Technically speaking, Germany's "unbeaten" record of zero deaths was broken on March 8.

A 60-year-old tourist to Egypt died of new pneumonia, the first death of a German citizen in the outbreak. But for ordinary Germans, the fact that the man died in Egypt, where testing conditions and medical facilities were relatively poor, seemed to confirm Germany's well-established epidemic prevention measures.

As Stefan Moritz, a German epidemiologist, puts it, "after all, we have the best and most expensive health care system in the world, and if we're not prepared, then who is? "

###Disorder and hidden trouble

Zero deaths, on the one hand, is indeed a comment on Germany's epidemic, but on the other hand it can be understood as the last fig leaf of the country's leaky health establishment.

At present, with the continuous increase in the number of confirmed, in the detection link has a wide range of hot lines, detection points full and other problems. The three-tier triage system has also resulted in cross-fertilization between the health sector and hospitals or clinics. In addition, the European logistics system did not enter the state of emergency, which also led to test kits in the weekend off period can not be delivered to the relevant agencies.

Germany's more serious problem is the chain of transmission cut and continue.

In the state of North rhine-westphalia, which has a concentration of nearly half of all cases in Germany, all cases follow the chain of transmission and can almost always be traced to the small town of Heinsberg.

On Feb. 25, a middle-aged couple in the town was identified by the authorities and their social networks tracked, but the virus exploded here. There's only one reason: Mardi Gras.

"It is precisely because we are in the early stages of the epidemic that targeted action should be taken, " Professor Dorsten may be disappointed. While the German authorities have implemented the first part of surveillance and containment, the second, more critical part of the chain of transmission, is flawed.

Late February is the traditional carnival season in the great German cities of the Rhine River Basin. Even the small town of Hines Berg had more than 300 people attending the town's celebrations, and the couple, the source of the outbreak, took part in a carnival at the DÜSSELDORF, düsseldorf draws an average of 400,000 people a year.

The first case of Wehrmacht's disease came from contact with the couple at the DÜSSELDORF. The regional Mardi Gras, combined with Ruhr, Germany's most populous state, is the main reason why North rhine-westphalia is Germany's "Hubei" .

The carnival is long over, but the beleaguered German authorities have not learned their lesson. In contrast to neighbouring Switzerland, which just days ago announced it was shutting down all major events involving more than 1,000 people, Germany has done nothing but close international exhibitions, including the industrial exhibition in Hanover.

Whether it is the closure of Italian schools and universities, the opening of Serie A games, or the closure of the northern regions, including Lombardy, these extraordinary measures are not considered by the German federal government.

The Bundesliga Games, in particular, which were the most crowded, are still going on normally. Even though Health Minister Spann suggested on the 8th that the Bundesliga match be postponed or held in an empty venue, as the Health Ministry has no authority over the DFB, the measures at the Fußball-Bundesliga venue have so far been limited to spraying disinfectant.

One of the most high profile was the Mönchengladbach against Revierderby in Dortmund on July 7, in Hines Berg, North Rhine Westphalia, less than 20 km from the Mönchengladbach. The 53,000-man Borussia-Park were still packed.

While the Bundesliga is firing on all cylinders, wearing a mask is still ignored. At all of Fußball-Bundesliga's games this weekend, almost no one wore a mask.

The idea that normal people do not need to wear masks is, as always, supported by experts. "Even if you wear a mask, the goal is to avoid touching your nose and mouth, not to stop the Aerosol, " said Morize, a communications expert. Only confirmed patients need to wear FFP3 masks because normal masks are not airtight enough to block the virus, which is why health care workers still need FFP3 masks."

For the "square-headed" Germans, the conclusion that the new coronavirus is not scary is based on the fact that there are no deaths.

Each year, the flu virus kills more than 100 people in Germany, with a mortality rate of about 0.1 to 0.2 percent, according to the Robert Koch, Germany's leading virologist. And even taking into account the German tourists who died in Egypt, the current fatality rate of the new coronavirus is indeed less than that of the common flu.

However, the trend in the number of confirmed cases is no different in Germany than in the early days of the Italian outbreak. The question is simply: Will Germany, with its 83m ageing population, be the next Italy?
